<br>
Is there a difference between &quot;good&quot; brainwashing and &quot;bad&quot; brainwashing? Absolutely not. Concerning the individual's own freedom, uniqueness, individuality, there is absolutely no difference between &quot;good&quot; or &quot;bad&quot; brainwashing. Both supporess the individual's own originality. Both teach the individual not to think for himself or make risky decisions, but rather to follow pre-chosen paths given to him by society. Brainwashing is &quot;bad&quot; in that it is not helpful to the individual's spiritual growth, infact it is the opposite. It makes him blind and deaf, it binds him. Whether it be &quot;good&quot; or &quot;bad&quot; brainwashing is just by circumstance, and it can change at any moment. One minute it's &quot;good&quot;, the next it's &quot;bad&quot;... and to the individual being brainwashed he can make no distinction between the two, because his own intuition has been suppressed and weakened so much.<br>
<br>
Teaching in and of itself is not brainwashing. What goes on in our schools is not teaching, but rather conditioning/brainwashing. Information can transferred from one person to another and viewed as just that: information to be observed, and applied as neccessary, but not to become attached to. That, I think, is true teaching. Someone can present information to me, and I can absorb it and recall it, and (here's the important part) apply it to life's situations *AT MY OWN DISCRETION*. Teaching is presenting factual information, or even guidance WITHOUT any moral attachment. Brainwashing is giving someone information and expecting, or forcing, them to take it &quot;blindly&quot;, not to question it, to blindly accept it as &quot;true&quot; or &quot;the only way&quot;. A good example of this is drugs. Teaching someone about drugs would be to teach them all information, all health risks, all possible benefits, all effects, etc. Teaching is educating a person so that they can freely make their own decision, considering all the risks and benefits, pros and cons. And if he decides to make a decision, having full awareness of possible risks, and ends up harming himself, then nobody is to blame but himself. And even then, it's not something &quot;bad&quot; ... it's just a conscious decision he decided to make, and now he can only accept the result (for he should have accepted it before it even happened). Brainwashing, or conditioning, however, is saying &quot;Drugs are bad. Just say no. We won't tell you why they are bad, but we say they're bad and you shouldn't question us. Don't bother to educate yourself, don't bother to do any research, just say NO and let that be the end of it.&quot; ... This is magnified further by presenting *ONLY* &quot;bad&quot; information. For example, showing the rare yet &quot;extremely negative&quot; situation of an unstable person taking hallucinogenic drugs which may result in a man stabbing someone else. &quot;Extreme&quot; (yet for the most part rare) situations like this are presented to make &quot;drugs&quot; (no distinction at all between the wide variety of drugs) look &quot;bad&quot;, when infact the situation may have been extremely rare, and mostly due to the fact that the person in question was unstable to begin with.<br>
<br>
The same person could have come to the same result on alcohol. And many people DO, yet we don't hear so much about those incidents because society says alcohol is &quot;acceptable&quot;, even though it can be just as dangerous, and in many cases much more dangerous. We don't hear about all the domestic cases of abuse and murder resulting from alcohol consumption. (albeit indirectly -- meaning that the alcohol only allowed for negative tendencies to be released which the unstable man has usually kept bottled up or suppressed. The alcohol wasn't the &quot;cause&quot;, but rather an instrument used by the man)<br>
<br>
&quot;Freedom&quot; I think should best be decribed as &quot;Freedom to make your own decisions and walk your own path, as long as those decisions don't interfere with someone else's direct freedom to make their own decisions and choose their own paths&quot;. Not freedom to &quot;do whatever the fuck you want, whenever the fuck you want, without regard for anyone else&quot;, but rather freedom of CHOICE, freedom to be presented options, and choose among those options without anyone else condemning you (or praising you, for both are ultimately destructive), or without anyone else prodding you to choose one option over the other.<br>
<br>
Along with freedom comes the great responsibility of COMPASSION. To have your own freedom, you also have to allow others the same privilege. You can make your own decisions, but also keep in mind how it will directly affect others, or how it will stand in the way of their freedom. For freedom, you must also learn to be selfless, to step aside for another person, to not be so intrusive and overbearing. I don't mean that you should over-worry about how every action you do will possibly affect someone else, but rather to carry a general understanding, compassion and consideration for others, for their individuality, for their originality, for their uniqueness, for their freedom to consciously make their own decisions.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>&quot;Brainwashing&quot; is a perjorative term for a process which goes on all the time: the transmission of ideas and prejudices from one person to another. Some of those ideas and prejudices are fallacious (example: a few people still believe that black people are less intelligent than white people).<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
&quot;a few people still believe that black people are less intelligent than white people&quot; ... just as many people still foolishly believe there are black people and white people, and not just people. So many people cry out about racism, about racial discrimination, yet it still exists by their very own doing. A line is still being drawn between people of different skin tone or place of origin. A line is still being drawn to seperate and categorize people based on these things. As long as these lines exist, then racial discrimination and prejudice will still exist. If we started categorizing people by the color of their eyes, and creating labels for the different categories, then the same prejudices would ultimately rear their dispicable heads (as I believe has been demonstrated in the past, via Hitler and his ideas of blonde-haired, blue-eyed utopia). For racial prejudice and discrimination to be eradicated, we must first dissolve the seperating lines. A person's skin tone (really just varying tones of the same skin... the same &quot;black&quot; tones are evident in a white man's freckles even!) should have absolutely no more significance than the size of his nose, his ears, the color of his eyes, or any other form of appearance. No prejudice should be formed based on any of those factors, and conversly, no special treatment should be given based on any of those factors either, for that still promotes the idea that a man's appearance/color of skin has some significance on his social standing or social benefits. I am disgusted by all the &quot;special treatment&quot; organizations and benefits to people of so-called ethnic minority groups... and even to females regardless of ethnic background or appearance. People realized a situation of prejudice, and instead of taking the proper steps to eradicate it, they are now simply swinging the pendulum in the opposite direction. Ultimately, the results will be just as ugly and disastrous, because the underlying problem is still there. Only the &quot;face&quot;, or surface, has changed.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I can sum this up in one sentence: Positive brainwashing creates freedom.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is disgusting. Brainwashing, by nature, can not create freedom. It is intrusive, overbearing, interfering, suppressive, destructive. No form of brainwashing, whether deemed &quot;positive&quot; or &quot;negative&quot; by society, can ultimately be helpful to the individual's own growth. Brainwashing, social conditioning, will always create bondage.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> religion = brainwashing<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Religion in and of itself is not brainwashing. The act of trying to &quot;convert&quot; others, of trying to persuade others to believe as you do, to try and transfer your own philosophies and morals onto others as &quot;the right way&quot;... that IS. It might better be said that &quot;organized religion=brainwashing&quot;, but even that can't apply to all circumstances and should probably be avoided.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
I INTEND to brainwash her that smoking is bad.<br>
<br>
I INTEND to brainwash her that drinking is bad.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
