[edit] fixed spellings <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=328193"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.geocities.com/hibashirasakai/HibashiraNewHalfSize.txt"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hibashira>Hibashira</A> at: 8/18/03 2:26 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub228.ezboard.com/bxevserverboards.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mallain>Mallain</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered Member</span><br>  Posts: 10<br> <font color=#330000>(8/18/03 4:46 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub228.ezboard.com/fxevserverboardsfrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=935.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Social Brainwashing</span><hr size=1> There's a difference between educating someone, and flat out telling them to do or not do something because you've decided for them. Using crack as an example, telling someone &quot;crack is bad&quot; is not teaching them anything at all. It's simply telling them not to do something, without explaining the reasons why or even giving them a choice in the matter. To actually educate them on the matter would be to teach them how the drug works chemically, what effects it has on the body &amp; mind, both positive and negative, the fact that it is physically addictive, and what chemical process causes it to be, etc. You can say &quot;In my opinion you would be wise not to smoke crack, but the decision is still yours, and since I should not be making the decision for you (either forcibly or subtly) I should at least do my best to educate you, so that you can make the decision that you feel is best for you&quot;, but to tell them &quot;Don't smoke crack because it's a drug and drugs are bad because DARE tells me so&quot; and expect them to blindly follow that without at least questioning the matter. Unfortunately, many people DO blindly accept what society tells them without a single question, especially (but not only) during childhood/pre-teen years.<br>
<br>
Experience is by far the greatest teacher ever. The only way to know what fire feels like is to get burned, but even with that in mind I wouldn't suggest that people go around blindly jumping into fires or ingesting everything they can get their hands on without first educating themselves about the matter in question.<br>
<br>
Since I don't want this to turn into a &quot;drug&quot; thread and only used that as an example, I'll present another example: Extreme sports. Snow skiing, rock climbing, etc. Should I go around telling people that extreme sports are bad, simply because I personally don't think the benefits outweigh the risks? I may think it's stupid to jump down a steep, snow-covered mountain, but does that give me any right to tell other people whether they should or shouldn't, especially if I've never done so myself? Obviously someone shouldn't go jumping down a mountain without first educating themselves about the possible risks, which in this case should be fairly obvious, but even so it would be wise to have other people describe their first-hand experiences and suggestions so that you can weigh the pros and cons and make your own decision without someone trying to impose their own moral standards upon you.<br>
<br>
Death is a very real possibility in extreme sports, and in many other things in life. Nevertheless, people still choose to do such things even with death as a possible risk. They must accept the fact that they could very well die, and if they think the experience is worth it, even with that possibility in mind, then nobody should tell them otherwise. Ultimately, it is their decision to make, and I would much rather them make an educated decision than an uneducated one, when it comes to matters like this anyway.<br>
<br>
Jumping into things blindly is also a decision one can make. If they want to jump into things without learning about possible benefits or risks, then that also is their decision. They have made the decision to play the &quot;fool&quot; (not as a derogatory term), and that can have its own benefits, but can also have many risks... and if an individual makes a conscious decision to play the &quot;fool&quot; and then encounters harmful consequences, that is something he must accept. There is no &quot;good&quot; or &quot;bad&quot;, &quot;fortunate&quot; or &quot;unfortunate&quot; about it...<br>
<br>
But that's not the point... the point is, the decision, the choice should always be left up to the individual in question. Not their friends, not their family, not their society, not their leaders, not anyone but themselves. Nobody should try and persuade someone else's decision one way or another, whether for good or for bad, because either way impedes upon the individual's free will. If you truely care about someone, how can you try and force them to act in a way suitable or acceptable to you? How does that help them grow as a person? It teaches them nothing other than to blindly obey society (of wich the family and friends are just a portion of). If you truely care about someone, you can do your best to help them learn... whether that means spending time to explain your own first-hand experiences, or (when you have no experience with the matter in question) directing them to someone who can. If you try and force your own beliefs and morals upon someone, you're only forcing them to be an extension of yourself, and suppressing their own originality. To help someone grow and learn is to allow them to be themselves, to consciously make their own choices, to express their originality and individuality, no matter how different from you that may be.<br>
<br>
Going back to the fire thing real quick:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>By your own logic, one should get burnt to learn that fire is not a toy? That's a silly notion, don't you agree?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It's not silly even in the slightest. How else will you know that fire is not a toy? Even if people tell you, you'll still never know from your own experience. The only way to know is to experience it, then you don't need anyone to tell you one way or another, you can decide based on your own experience.<br>
<br>
If you think telling someone about something is as good as experiencing it first-hand, then I suppose you wouldn't mind being locked in a bare room, being allowed no access to the outside world, yet having someone sitting next to you describing to you all the wonders of life. It might be hard to imagine since you've experienced so many things in life, but imagine raising a child in this way. Imagine not allowing them to see the sky, and just describing to them what it looks like. Imagine them never having seen the eyes of another person, or felt the loving carress of a mother. Will it suffice to simply describe these things to the child, without them ever experiencing them? Is that any way to live life, if indeed you could even call it living? <p><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=769191">v009=4f:xxxxxor</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
