Actually no. Thats not a silly notion. In fact, I'd be willing to bed a good majority of children &quot;Touch&quot; something that their parents said is &quot;Hot&quot;, only to get burned, and never, ever do it again. I know I did.<br>
<br>
Same goes for Stinging nettles (Poison Ivy?), Climbing up walls and falling, and a million other things that children learn by doing and getting hurt. It's this important thing, called experience.<br>
<br>
Like Everquest. How much can you really know about the game if you're only told about it. I thought I knew everything about some encounters. Then I faced them, and realised I didn't really know a whole Lot. I learned, the hard way, failed got back and learned from the mistakes. It's part of the human experience. <br>
<br>
The same goes for conditioning your children in anything more than the basic requirements of society, IE : don't steal, don't kill. This conditioning was essential during the evolution of man, In a society, you need rules, and the best way to pass those rules down is for the child to be conditioned. As society has grown, what is being conditioned has too. Racism, Abuse, and much more is passed from generation to generation. On top of that, In this era of protection people begin to forget it's the mistakes we learn more from. Trying to keep those you love safe can end up working against you.<br>
<br>
Not you, Not I, Not anyone, can know how to live life by being told.We have to live it. We have to make mistakes.<br>
<br>
Whether they are good or bad mistakes is irrelevant. <br>
<br>
For your examples, you can brainwash you're child to want to go to college. But wouldn't her going to college to make you happy hurt her wellbeing and growth more than not going to college because that isn't what she wants to do?<br>
<br>
Drinking, especially socially has a great deal of benefit, and good points. It's a great way to unwind, relax and have fun. I can say that I'm better off drinking socially as I do than if I wasn't. For starters, I wouldn't have met my Girlfriend. Whether it would work out that way with your daughter, neither you, nor I can say. And for the sheer fact that you require to be 18 (21 in the US) to drink, says that the choice will be up to that person, they'll be old enough.<br>
<br>
For Smoking, well, I'm probably worse off by smoking, But i'll tell you what, While you may not like it, smoking can cause growth in a person. Starting smoking, was the last &quot;Bad&quot; thing I did to make myself look &quot;Cool&quot; to my friends. I don't know how it would have turned out if I hadn't started. But I know I wouldn't have been nearly as happy. It's a knock on effect of causes and choices, but it's a part of the outcome.<br>
<br>
You see, Every single thing you can choose to 'condition' your kids with can be a learning experience, something to make that person grow and develop. You never know, If you didn't brainwash your child to hate smoking, and they started smoking, and gave up,  the strength they summon to quit smoking could stay with them and could become a direct cause for them to go into politics and eventually become president. You never know what is a learning experience for a person, hell, Even If you ARE that person.<br>
