<br>
I agree.<br>
<br>
My father tried the &quot;no smoking, no drinking&quot; conditioning with me.  What he never understood was that it is more important to model the behaviors you want from your children rather than simply saying &quot;no, you can not do that&quot;.<br>
<br>
My dad drank and smoked while lecturing me about how bad it was.  I always figured if he could do it so could I and he must be telling me it was bad because it was really fun and he wanted all the fun to himself.<br>
<br>
With my daughter it is very different.  I talk to her, I show her concrete examples from my life.  Those examples show how too much of anything can be bad.  I teach her moderation, I think that is so important, for example...<br>
<br>
Me  &quot;I would rather you not drink until you are of a legal age, but I did not wait and I do not expect you will either.&quot;<br>
<br>
Her  &quot;Is it ok to drink a little?&quot;<br>
<br>
Me  &quot;Moderation is a good thing, people go out to parties and bars all the time and have just a couple of drinks, there is no real harm in that so long as you are not breaking any laws.&quot;<br>
<br>
Her  &quot;If I went to a party and had too much to drink what do I do?&quot;<br>
<br>
Me  &quot;You call me, I'll come get you and your friends and make sure everyone gets home safely, no questions asked&quot;<br>
<br>
Those are the types of conversations I have with my 11 year old.  It scares the hell out of me at times, but she and I share something I never had with my parents.  She knows that she can come to me with any question and I will answer it, even if it means saying that I do not know but we can go look it up on the net.<br>
<br>
Going to college was mentioned, IMHO it is how you bring this up that matters.  I point to my ex-wife and her family, all 9 kids went to college and have very successful careers vs me.  The high school drop out who made piss poor choices and ended up stuck doing work that I was too damn smart for.<br>
<br>
In the end I think she will go to college, not because I want her to but because I have found a way to show her in terms she can understand how a college education opens doors that are often otherwise closed.<br>
<br>
When dealing with young kids presentation is everything.  Answers like &quot;Because I said so&quot; followed with behaviors that come across with the modeling of &quot;do as I say not as I do&quot; lead to conditioning that most often blows up in the parents face once the child becomes a young adult.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'm just saying that keeping loved ones safe and happy is not as clean and simple as conditioning.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
